Color Changes



The color syntax is moving to functions that accept alpha (transparency) without having the change the function name. For example, if you wanted pure blue in the CSS3 days, you might do rgb(0, 0, 255). Today, however, you can do it no-comma style (both work): rgb(0 0 255), and then add alpha without using a different function: rgb(0 0 255 / 0.5). Same exact situation for hsl(). Just a small nicety, and how future color functions will only work.



Speaking of future color syntaxes:



P3 color or ‚Äúdisplay-p3‚Äù is coming via the color() function.lab() color is another new color space. It ‚Äúrepresents the entire range of color that humans can see.‚Äùlch() is another new color space. hwb() is another new color space for humans.







body {
 font-family: 'Recursive', sans-serif;
 font-weight: 950;
 font-variation-settings: 'MONO' 1, 'CASL' 1;
}





Variable Fonts



Web fonts became a big thing in CSS3. Now there are variable fonts. You might as well know they exist. They both unlock some cool design possibilities and can sometimes be good for performance (like no longer needing to load different font files for bold and italic versions of the same font, for example). There is a such thing as color fonts too, but I‚Äôd say they haven‚Äôt seen much popularity on the web, despite the support.







