Paths



SVG has also exploded since CSS3. You can straight up crop any element into shapes via clip-path, bringing SVG-like qualities to CSS. Not only that, but you can animate elements along paths, float elements along paths, and even update the paths of SVG elements.



These all feel kind of spirtually connected to me:



clip-path ‚Äî allows us to literally crop elements into shapes.masks ‚Äî similar to clipping, but a mask can have other qualities like being based on the alpha channel of the mask.offset-path ‚Äî provides a path that an element can be placed on, generally for the purpose of animating it along that path.shape-outside ‚Äî provides a path on a floated element that other elements wrap around. d ‚Äî an SVG‚Äôs d attribute on a <path> can be updated via CSS.







