  filter: 
    blur(1px)
    grayscale(1);
}

.site-header {
  backdrop-filter: 
    blur(10px);
}

.styled-quote {
  mix-blend-mode: 
    exclusion;
} 





CSS Filters



There is a lot of image manipulation (not to mention other DOM elements) that is possible these days directly in CSS. There is quite literally filter, but its got friends and they all have different uses. 



These all feel kind of spirtually connected to me:



filter ‚Äî all sorts of useful Photoshop-like effects like brightness, contrast, grayscale, sautration, etc. Blurring is a really unique power.background-blend-mode ‚Äî again, evocative of Photoshop in how you can blend layers. Multiply the layers to darken and combine. Overlay to mix the background and color. Lighten and darken are classic effects that have real utility in web design, and you never know when a more esoteric lighting effect will create a cool look.backdrop-filter ‚Äî the same abilities you have with filter, but they only apply to the background and not the entire element. Blurring just the background is a particularly useful effect.mix-blend-mode ‚Äî the same abilities you have with background-blend-mode, but for the entire element rather than bring limited to backgrounds.







import "https://unpkg.com/extra.css/confetti.js";



body {
  background: paint(extra-confetti);
  height: 100vh;
  margin: 0;
}





Houdini



Houdini is really a collection of technologies that are all essentially based around extending CSS with JavaScript, or at least at the intersection of CSS and JavaScript.



Paint API ‚Äî returns an image that is built from <canvas> APIs and can be controlled through custom properties.Properties & Values API / Typed OM ‚Äî gives types to values (e.g. 10px) that would have otherwise been strings.Layout API ‚Äî create your own display properties.Animation API



Combined, these make for some really awesome demos, though browser support is scattered. Part of the magic of Houdini is that it ships as Worklets that are pretty easy to import and use, so it has the potential to modularize powerful functionality while making it trivially easy to use.







